[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Java coverage**\n\nI'm considering the JVM agent and how adding `jvmArgs` with `add-opens` would apply to the Java 8 branch but not to Java 9. It seems like I might have to choose just one branch for coverage. Currently, the dynamic report shows that Java 8 is active and could cover around five aspects. I want to make sure I'm understanding this correctly and choosing the best path forward!\n\n**Evaluating test configuration**\n\nI’m looking at the coverage for my tests and noticing that 9 covers 3, but I still have some lines that need attention. Would it make sense to add a separate test class? I could configure `forkEvery=1` to have each class run in a separate JVM, or perhaps handle Java 9 and 8 with different classes? But would this violate the one-to-one mapping rule for dynamic classes? It’s an intricate balancing act!\n\n**Analyzing testing strategy**\n\nI’m running into an issue with my one-to-one mapping; existing tests like `Parquet_hadoopTest` could end up hitting different branches than `CleanUtilTest`, which might not be ideal. It’s tricky because the coverage calls for each class to be in its own file. I could use a single top-level test class with a JUnit Platform Suite, but that wouldn’t involve new processes per method. \n\nThere are also complications with dynamic class loading, like using reflection, which seems restricted in tests. What to do? It’s quite the conundrum!\n\n**Reviewing class loading issues**\n\nI’m facing challenges with dynamic class loading since it seems unsupported under native conditions, which can throw errors that prevent call sites from executing. There’s a rule about using specific patterns for dynamic class loading, but direct reflection in tests is not allowed. I wonder if building two separate processes with the same test class would work — but with the current guidelines, it probably won’t.\n\nMaybe 