[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating coverage instrumentation**\n\nI'm thinking about coverage instrumentation for a duplicate child-loaded class that should now be instrumented. If it deduplicates by class name and has already transformed the original, in the Java 9 branch, do dynamic accesses count the same? If the duplicate isn't transformed, it could mean no coverage. I need to enforce legacy coverage first by ordering in the same test class. Although, user mentions remaining legacy, which suggests the workflow report might aggregate previous attempts.\n\n**Considering coverage improvement**\n\nIf I force the legacy original, it might indicate five newly covered lines, but Java 9 coverage may still reflect the previous attempt. My goal is to cover the remaining lines, even if achieving that in one JVM is technically impossible. The coverage system seems to focus on the current test suite rather than cumulative totals, though the phrase \"newly covered since previous\" hints it compares to prior results. So, I need to be careful not to drop coverage and might consider splitting test classes and adjusting Gradle settings, but this could complicate things since JUnit can’t vary system properties before loading classes.\n\n**Evaluating Java testing strategy**\n\nI’m considering whether we can create `CleanUtilLegacyTest` without importing `CleanUtil`. It seems like we should have dedicated test files for each dynamic-access class. Currently, there's just `CleanUtilTest`, and I don’t want to add an additional file. There’s a lot of complexity around JUnit ordering and Java 9's URLClassLoader. If I run tests in separate JVMs, could that help with coverage? Gradle might allow me to define multiple test tasks to manage different Java versions. I'm trying to prioritize the legacy coverage properly.\n\n**Exploring TCK dynamic reporting**\n\nI’m considering whether the TCK dynamic report could include all test tasks, but it seems like the `javaTest` task may execute them all. I need to check the plugin to confirm. Configuring the default `test` to fork each test method might help, but I can't set two `java.version` values in one task. Creating a custom `legacyCleanUtilTest` task could be beneficial. Perhaps Gradle supports a way to set system properties right before the test method runs? I’m also wondering if JUnit’s ordering could assist, but I might need a new approach altogether.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_01d3ce057da11f900169fe56e57de4819d9fd8fe3c8f1b8c2a\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp_lb85DiB4S917oXZUUvqNWwC3fwaLzeeQIvY0l63qw5WlWBaAdEzieIcbuE46pY_Zd7cBDn2Q6YtpTN6XMG8tExSWFi-HN1C9zXulVGN0NZABDd3e-OZcvhKom5lGwuk6G58NQ6_G7mn5QVW8WYI_l5bWNIrPldnO3GznH5_OjvZ-rCr-J3UY-YIt4lZA3VrDG0Amz86mlNklNhwc_MtKq1AkA8wQAXSWIeYl860RBQv_7saL0_BSAESeAOWDQhe0qFYecEI5fWCUVnR4v75k72HBoGaeNz_RKbiWFYKayX0wYm7VuXRKCs15_-xK122qayQAo9vDARtYEKzHEDbzBfzcy75ME_d2Gy0OBr1Fq7YcVK3NnmjLXJhTuHda7e6v8_cZu27Q6YbC_ExFA8r_5coSqz-683eRLQ-418KGy7HDtci4dMYN3lPb4Ru35eGVzind1KEfPAcxx9VfoBMMZ53n7Qx3ianCPwpU5AutSaY0cfHVagiLGmu0qo4x7MPH6pYBxLTBFsqFlBo-gsiJX8QnI83fUsFTyjW7apJtEUEfwtsyBy2k1SkMyQrmgAJcVLxqQpTUYMqqqvkrQIjhiKn2CjzFaUrCT7GI0408-C3mrp_5Xt5vQ0mY65N_umLm_7OvFWNNap8cCIOCYUzM9vNs2IfvXsHxk8HoxavCV_Gpb4-qjXVGkMc9sSK0pOFwsayM9nt7zgIYpNsED7-8TFeM4wvywzzW42Z4fY4thLtWUmpOPm4tVaGuAUFfpWHpjJuyAU-ZySVNYa7OX1WKcR02QtQT-zfJIPQ8SI7uW8RYDcwa8Fi6HSazQMHd1tx58hcr_fX7eIxJvPnRBIR0hBGXjsLJtyPzPaT26SQtSBkutA3SKNzb_BFKtDh0eVpux0bVSccRsCxNbmTbk7dxrjdSvqPHT-n4A6hx84QyW-M6NFrHGfxsImsaFJxghr4CKzo-Gsl_VgVpgG0TTEicwSy7sLfVf1SHiajLJtEh-1UBsXo015yX8EQOdDA5tdJ8KYyHjZNeBW0gBULa4gtfANNTHyKSiX32sU7-DQWY4VyLvImrgYva9GANmFCjulXJVVcTpqvW7lSJB6cIpTe5BP4pSsRQPQkVpFTrQan-qLTIKU1sO26O4EXYC4p22NvTz80QTqF2_tYjAYjOax_FNiCyHwXA7WEll4RvKaMQ94EcQFTWdj7U4U9DxdRBs-sawjnBB5gfjti6o84jgi1Ei8qS8GqhXeXSXu4y1pejwaK94UDokGuANyrtODcpQnjWml1VzzoOpovWzTPBGgyddXQKiYwiTYCIQshskDYWql9K_ydvnsqLD7binptVl6ikTxnuSAyV